        </mj-text>
        <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.altdaily.co/email/images/an-dec-20-3.jpg" alt="Airbus maintains delivery lead over Boeing despite production challenges" href="https://www.altdaily.co" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">
          Airbus is on track to out-deliver Boeing for the sixth consecutive year, projecting 764 aircraft deliveries in 2024 compared to Boeing's 395. Despite a strong performance, including 80 jets delivered in November—a six-year high—Airbus is struggling to meet its revised target of 770 deliveries. Originally set at 800, the goal was lowered mid-year due to production delays and supply chain constraints.</p>
         <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">
         Meanwhile, Boeing has taken a more conservative approach following its 2018-2019 safety crises, focusing on rebuilding trust and reducing production rates. In contrast, Airbus has adopted an aggressive strategy, prioritizing deliveries even amid industry-wide delays. The company is negotiating with engine suppliers to prioritize Airbus over competitors to meet its targets.</p>
         <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">
         This tug-of-war underscores the contrasting strategies of the two aerospace giants, with Airbus leveraging its scale to dominate the market while navigating significant operational pressures.</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>
   

