          <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4;"><span style="font-size:20px; padding-right:5px;">→</span><strong>Palliser urges Rio Tinto listing review:</strong>   
         Activist investor Palliser Capital is <a href="https://www.bnnbloomberg.ca/business/company-news/2024/12/19/activist-palliser-pushes-rio-tinto-to-review-its-dual-listing/" target="_blank">pressing</a> Rio Tinto to review its dual listing structure, arguing it has cost investors $50 billion in value. Palliser submitted a resolution for an independent review ahead of Rio's annual meeting. While BHP ditched its dual listing in 2021, Rio CEO Jakob Stausholm remains firm that the current structure works due to its London-heavy investor base.</p>
          </mj-text>

          <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4;"><span style="font-size:20px; padding-right:5px;">→</span><strong>MidOcean CLO equity fund surpasses target:</strong>   
         MidOcean Partners <a href="https://www.privateequitywire.co.uk/midocean-partnerss-clo-equity-fund-surpasses-300m-target/" target="_blank">closed</a> its first CLO Equity Fund at $304 million, exceeding its $300 million target. Led by industry veterans Joseph Rotondo and Jamil Nathoo, the fund focuses on a defensive strategy, investing in diversified senior secured leveraged loans. Approximately 55% of capital has already been deployed across seven CLOs, representing $2.8 billion in assets under management. This aligns with MidOcean's broader momentum, including a recent $765 million raise for Tactical Credit III.</p>
          </mj-text>

          <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4;"><span style="font-size:20px; padding-right:5px;">→</span><strong>DLocal considers sale amid rising interest:</strong>   
         DLocal, the $3.6 billion Latin American payments provider, is <a href="https://www.privateequitywire.co.uk/general-atlantic-backed-dlocal-explores-sale/" target="_blank">exploring</a> a potential sale with Morgan Stanley facilitating discussions. Backed by General Atlantic, DLocal has drawn interest from private equity and fintech firms as the sector consolidates. Challenges like currency fluctuations and competition have pressured its valuation, but improved transaction volumes in some markets show resilience. This is their second attempt at selling as the previous discussion concluded in disagreement over financial terms. DLocal reported a 5% increase in gross profit in its latest quarterly earnings.</p>
          </mj-text>

