          South Korea's financial regulator is urging lenders to <a href="https://www.bnnbloomberg.ca/business/international/2024/12/19/korean-lenders-to-clean-up-bulk-of-property-loans-amid-turmoil/" target="_blank">clean up</a> $11.2 billion troubled real estate loans by mid-2025, addressing over 70% of risky property project exposure. This follows earlier steps to stabilize the market amid political turmoil impacting economic growth. The Financial Supervisory Service emphasized stable management of these risks, encouraging swift action from financial institutions. While the regulator claims limited impact on funding markets, Bank of Korea Governor Rhee Chang-yong cautioned that the turmoil could cut growth forecasts.</p>
