    <mj-section css-class="mj_section" background-color="#ffffff">
      <mj-column>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="             
              font-size: 20px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 500;
              margin-top: 2px !important;">How does quantitative easing inflate asset prices and inequality?</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.altdaily.co/email/images/an-dec-20-4.jpg" alt="How does quantitative easing inflate asset prices and inequality?" href="https://www.altdaily.co" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">Quantitative easing is a monetary policy tool where central banks purchase government bonds and other securities to inject liquidity into the economy. While QE aims to stimulate growth during economic downturns, it often inflates asset prices and exacerbates inequality.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">
          By lowering interest rates and increasing the money supply, QE encourages borrowing and investment. However, much of this liquidity flows into financial markets, driving up the prices of stocks, bonds, and real estate. Wealthy individuals, who are more likely to own these assets, benefit disproportionately, while those with limited exposure to investments see fewer gains.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">
          Additionally, QE can widen the gap between wages and asset returns. While workers see slow wage growth, investors reap substantial profits from inflated asset prices. This disparity amplifies wealth inequality over time. Though QE supports economic recovery, its uneven distribution of benefits highlights the need for complementary policies addressing broader societal inequities.</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>
