        <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">
        Value at risk (VaR) estimates the maximum potential loss an investment might face over a specific time frame, given normal market conditions at a specific confidence level. For example, if a portfolio has a VaR of $10,000 at a 95% confidence level, it means there’s a 95% chance the loss won’t exceed $10,000 in the given period. It’s a way to gauge risk.
        </p>
